house.gov/|House website}}\n}}\n'''Karen Christine Handel''' ([[maiden name|n\u00e9e]] '''Walker'''; born April 18, 1962) is an [[United States|American]] businesswoman, politician, and member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] for [[Georgia's 6th congressional district]]. In 2017, she became the first Republican woman from Georgia elected to [[United States Congress|Congress]] after defeating Democratic candidate [[Jon Ossoff]] in a [[Georgia's 6th congressional district special election, 2017|special election]] to fill [[Tom Price (American politician)|Tom Price]]'s vacancy in [[Georgia's 6th congressional district]]; this special election remains the most expensive congressional race in American history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/gop-holds-georgia-seat-special-election|title=Karen Handel Keeps Georgia Seat in GOP Hands|date=June 21, 2017|website=Roll Call}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/20/us/politics/karen-handel-georgia-special-election.html|title=Karen Handel Wins Georgia Special Election, Fending Off Upstart Democrat|last=Martin|first=Jonathan|date=June 20, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 21, 2017|last2=Fausset|first2=Richard|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nHandel previously served as the 26th [[Secretary of State of Georgia]]. A member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], Handel worked in business before entering politics. First elected in 2003, she chaired the [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton County]] Board of Commissioners until 2006, and then was elected and served as Georgia's Secretary of State from 2007 to 2010.\n\nIn 2011, Handel was appointed Senior Vice President of public policy at [[Susan G. Komen for the Cure]], a charity in the cause of fighting breast cancer,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ww5.komen.org/uploadedFiles/Content_Binaries/Karen%20Handel%204.27.11.pdf |title=Komen.org |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=January 26, 2013}}</ref> and left on February 7, 2012, following the foundation's controversial decision to eliminate and then later restore funding for [[Planned Parenthood]], an organization to which she was opposed.<ref name=\"Washington_Post_Handel_resigns\" />\n\n==Early life==\nHandel was born Karen Christine Walker<ref name=\"FEC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fec.gov/data/candidate/H8GA06286/?election_full=False&cycle=2018|title=Handel, Karen Christine - Candidate overview|publisher=Federal Election Commission|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Maryland native\">{{cite web|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/breaking/bs-hs-komen-karen-handel-20120203-story.html|title= Komen controversy puts Maryland native in spotlight |author=Wenger, Yvonne, and Rosen, Jill|work=Baltimore Sun|date=February 3, 2012|accessdate=June 20, 2017}}</ref> in [[Washington, D.C.]] on April 18, 1962,<ref name=\"HandelKarenCongressBio2017\">{{cite news |last= |first= |date= |title=Handel, Karen, (1962 - ) |url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=H001078 |work=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress |publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office |location=[[Washington, DC]] |access-date=June 29, 2017 |quote=HANDEL, Karen, a Representative from Georgia; born in Washington, District of Columbia, April 18, 1962}}</ref> and grew up in [[Upper Marlboro, Maryland]].<ref name=\"HandelKarenCongressBio2017\"/><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Karen Handel Biography|journal=[[Georgia Secretary of State]]|url=http://www.sos.ga.gov/misc/bio.htm|accessdate=July 25, 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100728045552/http://www.sos.ga.gov/misc/bio.htm |archivedate=July 28, 2010}}</ref> After graduating in May 1980 from [[Frederick Douglass High School (Prince George's County, Maryland)|Frederick Douglass High School]]<ref name=\"HandelKarenCongressBio2017\"/> in Upper Marlboro,<ref name=\"HandelKarenCongressBio2017\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Galloway, J. |url=http://blogs.ajc.com/political-insider-jim-galloway/2009/06/29/on-the-education-of-karen-handel|title=On the high-school education of Karen Handel|publisher=Atlanta Journal Constitution|date=June 29, 2009|accessdate=January 26, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130619011555/http://blogs.ajc.com/political-insider-jim-galloway/2009/06/29/on-the-education-of-karen-handel|archivedate=June 19, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|first=Jim|last=Galloway|title=Karen Handel: \u2018Yes, I have a high school diploma\u2019|date=July 3, 2009|url=http://blogs.ajc.com/political-insider-jim-galloway/2009/07/03/karen-handel-yes-i-have-a-high-school-diploma|work=[[Atlanta Journal Constitution]]|accessdate=July 26, 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101109000235/http://blogs.ajc.com/political-insider-jim-galloway/2009/07/03/karen-handel-yes-i-have-a-high-school-diploma|archivedate=November 9, 2010}}</ref> Handel attended both [[Prince George's Community College]], in [[Largo, Maryland]],<ref name=\"HandelKarenCongressBio2017\"/> and the [[University of Maryland, University College]], in [[Adelphi, Maryland]],<ref name=\"HandelKarenCongressBio2017\"/> but did not complete any degree.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://onlineathens.com/stories/080706/election_20060807023.shtml|title=Secretary of state candidates not focused on issues|date=August 7, 2006|work=Athens Banner-Herald|accessdate=October 9, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809102405/http://onlineathens.com/stories/080706/election_20060807023.shtml|archive-date=August 9, 2017|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref> She then went to work for [[Hallmark Cards]]. Later, she served as deputy chief of staff to Vice President [[Dan Quayle]]'s wife, [[Marilyn Quayle|Marilyn]],<ref name=\"DeneryAJC04182017\"/> where she worked to promote [[breast cancer]] awareness and research.<ref>{{cite news|ref=harv|newspaper=Times-Georgian|title=Handel, candidate for Ga. gov., makes early campaign stop in Carrollton|year=2009|url=http://times-georgian.com/pages/full_story/push?article-Handel-+candidate+for+Ga-+gov-+makes+early+campaign+stop+in+Carrollton%20&id=3285499}}{{dead link|date=May 2017|bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref>\n\nHandel worked at several major companies including global eye care company [[Ciba Vision]] and international accounting firm [[KPMG]].<ref>{{Cite news|first= Ryan|last=Mahoney|title=Business backs Handel for secretary of state|url=http://atlanta.bizjournals.com/atlanta/stories/2005/07/25/daily63.html?jst=b_ln_hl|publisher=[[Atlanta Business Chronicle]]|date=July 28, 2005|accessdate=July 20, 2009}}</ref> She served as president and CEO of the Greater Fulton County [[Chamber of Commerce]]. From December 2002 to November 2003, Handel served as deputy chief of staff to Georgia Governor [[Sonny Perdue]], where she worked as a policy advisor and supervised constituent services, the Governor's Mansion, and general administration services.<ref name=\"HandelKarenCongressBio2017\"/><ref name=\"DeneryAJC04182017\">{{cite news |last=Denery |first=Jim |date=April 18, 2017 |title=Who is Karen Handel? |url=http://www.ajc.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/who-karen-handel/0S1kM1dYAtnRy4kaFJhDLN/ |work=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]] |location=[[Atlanta, Georgia]] |publisher=[[Cox Media Group|Cox Media Group LLC]] |access-date=May 18, 2017|quote=Her resume also includes leading the Fulton County Commission as its chairwoman; working in the office of Marilyn Quayle, the wife of then-Vice President Dan Quayle; and serving as deputy chief of staff to then-Gov. Sonny Perdue.}}</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\nIn November 2003, Handel was elected chairman of the [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton County]] Board of Commissioners in a special election to replace [[Mike Kenn]], receiving 58% of the popular vote and continued to serve in that role until 2006.<ref name=\"HandelKarenCongressBio2017\"/><ref name=\"DeneryAJC04182017\"/> She had run for commissioner unsuccessfully in November 2002, while serving as the president and CEO of North Fulton County Chamber of Commerce. Handel chose not to run for re-election as the chairman of the Fulton County Board of Commissioners in order to run for Georgia Secretary of State.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.daltondailycitizen.com/news/local_news/profile-karen-handel-a-planner-implemented-voter-id/article_2d64ad8e-a6d9-5a8e-b7a9-7f95023c5996.html|title=Profile: Karen Handel a planner, implemented Voter ID|last=Citizen|first=Aaron Gould Sheinin Dalton Daily|work=The Daily Citizen|access-date=May 23, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Secretary of State of Georgia==\n[[File:Handel.jpeg|thumb| Handel with [[Andy Foster]]]]\nIn August 2006, Handel won the Republican [[primary election]] for [[Secretary of State of Georgia]], defeating [[Georgia Senate|state Senator]] Bill Stephens of [[Canton, Georgia|Canton]].<ref>[http://www.dailyreportonline.com/id=1202552491493/Low-turnout-expected-for-Georgia-runoffs?slreturn=20170307161449 Low turnout expected for Georgia runoffs], Associated Press (August 8, 2006).</ref> Handel received 56.6% of the vote to Stephens' 42.4%.<ref name=sos>{{cite web|url=http://www.sos.state.ga.us/elections/election_results/2006_0808/federal.htm|title=Official Results of the August 8, 2006 Primary Runoff Election|publisher=Georgia Secretary of State|date=August 15, 2006}}</ref> In the November 2006 general election, Handel defeated Democratic nominee Gail Buckner, receiving 54.1% of the vote to Buckner's 41.8%.<ref>[http://sos.ga.gov/elections/election_results/2006_1107/006.htm Georgia Election Results: Official Results of the Tuesday, November 07, 2006 General Election], Georgia Secretary of State.</ref> Handel was the first elected Republican secretary of state in Georgia history.<ref>[http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/articles/government-politics/secretary-state Secretary of State], ''[[New Georgia Encyclopedia]]'' (last edited July 25, 2016).</ref> She served as Georgia Secretary of State from 2007 to 2009.<ref name=\"HandelKarenCongressBio2017\"/>\n\nSoon after taking office as Georgia Secretary of State, Handel began a project to purge voter rolls.<ref name=\"BoudreauBronstein\">Abbie Boudreau & Scott Bronstein, [http://www.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/10/26/voter.suppression/ Some voters 'purged' from voter rolls], CNN  Special Investigations Unit (October 26, 2008).</ref> The procedure involved matching data with information in various sources such as the Georgia Department of Driver Services database or the Social Security Administration database.<ref name=\"NCSL2009\">[http://www.ncsl.org/Portals/1/documents/legismgt/elect/Canvass_Vol10.pdf\"THE CANVASS States and Election Reform\u00ae A Newsletter for Legislatures\"], NCSL, December 2009.</ref><ref name=\"NCSL2009\"/>  Some eligible voters were told that they were \"non-citizens\" although in fact they were citizens.<ref name=\"BoudreauBronstein\"/> [[Voter suppression]] allegations were raised and the rule became the subject of a federal lawsuit by the [[ACLU]] of Georgia and [[Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund|MALDEF]], which accused Handel's office of engaging in a \"systematic purging procedure\" expressly barred by federal law within 90 days of elections.<ref name=\"BoudreauBronstein\"/><ref name=\"Fox2009\">[http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2009/06/02/justice-department-knocks-georgia-rule-requiring-voters-prove-citizenship.html \"Justice Department Knocks Down Georgia Rule Requiring Voters Prove Citizenship\"], Fox News, June 2, 2009.</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the [[United States Department of Justice Civil Rights Division]] (DOJ) ordered a halt to the state's \"voter verification\" effort (denying it approval under the [[Voting Rights Act of 1965]]), determining that \"thousands of citizens who are in fact eligible to vote under Georgia law have been flagged\" and that the program was \"flawed ... [and] frequently subjects a disproportionate number of African-American, Asian and/or Hispanic voters to additional, and more importantly, erroneous burdens on the right to register to vote.\" This marked the first time since the 1990s that the Justice Department had denied approval to a change in Georgia election practice.<ref name=\"Fox2009\"/>\n\nHandel defended her program, asserting that it was appropriate and necessary.<ref name=\"Fox2009\"/> A federal judge in Atlanta later dismissed a lawsuit that had accused Handel's successor, Secretary of State Brian Kemp of illegally bumping Georgia voters off the state's rolls ahead of the 2016 presidential election. In the 21-page ruling, U.S. District Judge Timothy C. Batten Sr. said the state had taken a \"reasonable and nondiscriminatory\" approach in trying to reach voters who had not cast a ballot within the past 7 years to confirm their addresses.<ref>Kristina Torres, ''The Atlanta Journal-Constitution'', March 17, 2017.</ref>\n\n==2010 election==\n{{See also|Georgia gubernatorial election, 2010}}\nIn March 2009, Handel announced her decision to run for Georgia governor.<ref name=\"DeneryAJC04182017\"/>  Handel announced in December 2009 that she would resign as Secretary of State in order to focus on her campaign for governor in the 2010 election full-time.<ref>{{Cite news|first=James|last=Salzer|title=Handel quits as Secretary of State, says she's \"all in\" for governor\u2019s race|date=December 22, 2009|url=http://blogs.ajc.com/gold-dome-live/2009/12/22/handel-quits-as-secretary-of-state-says-shes-all-in-for-governors-race|work=[[Atlanta Journal Constitution]]|accessdate=July 25, 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100227144806/http://blogs.ajc.com/gold-dome-live/2009/12/22/handel-quits-as-secretary-of-state-says-shes-all-in-for-governors-race|archivedate=February 27, 2010}}</ref>\nOn July 20, 2010, in the Republican primary vote, Handel received 34% and former Congressman [[Nathan Deal]] received 23%.<ref>{{cite web|title=Unofficial And Incomplete Results of the Tuesday, July 20, 2010 General Primary Election|work=[[Georgia Secretary of State]]|url=http://sos.georgia.gov/elections/election_results/2010_0720/swall.htm|accessdate=July 25, 2010}}</ref> Since neither candidate received a majority, they faced off in the Republican gubernatorial run off on August 10, 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Shaila|last=Dewan|title=Georgia Will Have Republican Primary Runoff|date=July 20, 2010|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/21/us/politics/21georgiaweb.html|work=[[New York Times]]|page=A12|accessdate=July 26, 2010}}</ref>\n\nHandel received the endorsement of former Republican 2008 [[Vice President of the United States|Vice-Presidential]] candidate [[Sarah Palin]].<ref>{{Cite news|first=Jill|last=Vejnoska|title=Palin nods, and suddenly a Georgia race wakes up|date=July 25, 2010|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/palin-nods-and-suddenly-577969.html|work=[[Atlanta Journal Constitution]]|accessdate=July 26, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Shannon|last=McCaffrey|title=Palin effect rocks Georgia GOP primary|date=July 22, 2010|agency=Associated Press|url=http://www.macon.com/2010/07/22/1203282/palin-effect-rocks-georgia-primary.html|work=[[Macon Telegraph]]|accessdate=July 25, 2010|quote=Post-Palin, Handel catapulted to the top of a crowded field in Tuesday's primary election and won a spot in an Aug. 10 GOP runoff \u2014 the first woman to emerge from a gubernatorial primary in Georgia history.|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100723072055/http://www.macon.com/2010/07/22/1203282/palin-effect-rocks-georgia-primary.html|archivedate=July 23, 2010}}</ref> as well as former Republican presidential candidate [[Mitt Romney]].<ref>Ed Hornick, [http://www.cnn.com/2010/POLITICS/08/10/conservative.endorsements/ Big-time conservatives line up behind rival candidates], CNN.com, August 10, 2010.</ref>\n\nThe primary campaign was particularly heated, and Handel's past association with the gay rights group [[Log Cabin Republicans]] became an issue. Handel denied membership with Log Cabin Republicans.<ref name=Politifact>{{cite web |url=http://www.politifact.com/georgia/statements/2010/jun/16/karen-handel/did-handel-ever-joing-log-cabin-republicans |title=Did Handel ever join the Log Cabin Republicans? |publisher=Politifact |date=June 9, 2010 |accessdate=January 26, 2013}}</ref> Handel lost the runoff election to Deal by 50.2% to 49.8% \u2014 with about 2,500 votes separating them out of nearly 580,000 cast.<ref name=\"HandelKarenCongressBio2017\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sos.georgia.gov/elections/election_results/2010_0810/0020001.htm|title=Governor|publisher=Sos.georgia.gov|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref> She declined to request a recount and conceded to Deal the next day.\n\n==Susan G. Komen==\nIn April 2011, Handel was hired as senior vice president of public policy at [[breast cancer]] [[Charitable organization|charity]] [[Susan G. Komen for the Cure]] (\"Komen\"). In this position she was responsible for leading the organization\u2019s federal and state advocacy efforts, including management of Advocacy Alliance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peachpundit.com/2011/04/12/karen-handel-now-senior-vp-for-public-policy-with-susan-g-komen-for-the-cure|title=Karen Handel Now Senior VP For Public Policy With Susan G Komen For The Cure|publisher=Peach Pundit|date=April 12, 2011|accessdate=January 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of January 2012, Komen stated it would cut ties with [[Planned Parenthood]], the largest single provider of abortion services in the U.S.<ref>{{cite news|last=Crary|first=David|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/46209349/ns/health-womens_health/#.Tyie48VSQ-k|title=Planned Parenthood 'reeling' after losing charity funds|publisher=MSNBC|agency=Associated Press|date=January 31, 2012|accessdate=January 26, 2013}}</ref> The organization attributed the decision to a newly adopted policy not to fund organizations under investigation by a government agency. Republicans in Congress initiated an investigation into Planned Parenthood's alleged usage of federal funds to finance the organization's abortion services.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/susan-g-komen-foundation-pulls-planned-parenthood-funding|title=Susan G. Komen Foundation pulls Planned Parenthood funding|accessdate=March 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn February 2, 2012, [[Jeffrey Goldberg]] reported in ''[[The Atlantic]]'' that \"three sources with direct knowledge of the Komen decision-making process told me that the rule was adopted in order to create an excuse to cut-off Planned Parenthood.\" Goldberg further reported that his anonymous sources indicated \"the decision to create a rule that would cut funding to Planned Parenthood, according to these sources, was driven by the organization's new senior vice-president for public policy, Karen Handel, a former gubernatorial candidate from Georgia who is anti-abortion and who has stated that since she is 'pro-life, I do not support the mission of Planned Parenthood'\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2012/02/top-susan-g-komen-official-resigned-over-planned-parenthood-cave-in/252405|title=Top Susan G. Komen Official Resigned Over Planned Parenthood Cave-In|first=Jeffrey|last=Goldberg|publisher=The Atlantic|date=February 2, 2012|accessdate=January 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn February 5, 2012, ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' reported that \"emails between Komen leadership... confirm Handel's sole 'authority' in crafting and implementing the Planned Parenthood policy... Handel submitted the new grant criteria to Komen leadership in November and the board approved it in December, at which point Komen's top public health official resigned \"on the spot.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/02/05/karen-handel-susan-g-komen-decision-defund-planned-parenthood_n_1255948.html|title=Karen Handel, Susan G. Komen's Anti-Abortion VP, Drove Decision To Defund Planned Parenthood|first=Laura|last=Bassett|date=February 5, 2012|accessdate=April 20, 2017|via=Huff Post}}</ref>\n\nFour days after the decision to cut ties with Planned Parenthood, Komen reversed the decision and announced that it would amend the policy to \"make clear that disqualifying investigations must be criminal and conclusive in nature and not political\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/news/amy-davidson/why-komen-backed-down|title=Why Komen Backed Down|date=February 3, 2012|website=The New Yorker|accessdate=March 27, 2017}}</ref> A few days later, on February 7, 2012, Handel resigned from Komen.<ref name=Washington_Post_Handel_resigns>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/ezra-klein/post/komen-vice-president-karen-handel-resigns/2012/02/07/gIQAYP0WwQ_blog.html|work=The Washington Post|first1=Sarah|last1=Kliff|first2=N.C.|last2=Aizenman|title=Komen vice president Karen Handel resigns|date=February 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Los Angeles Times'' described Komen's decision to cut ties with Planned Parenthood as \"one of the great PR faux pas of the decade\", with Komen losing 22% of its funding in the subsequent fiscal year.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/hiltzik/la-fi-mh-susan-g-komen-20140108-story.html|title=Susan G. Komen Foundation discovers the price of playing politics|date=January 8, 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=March 27, 2017|issn=0458-3035}}</ref> Komen officials also attributed much of the lost funding to the decision to cut ties with Planned Parenthood.<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\n===Memoirs===\nOn September 11, 2012, Handel published a book, ''Planned Bullyhood'', about her tenure as vice president of public policy at Susan G. Komen for the Cure. In the book, Handel defended Komen's short-lived decision to end grants to Planned Parenthood.<ref name=\"thedailybeast.com\">{{cite web|last=Pesta|first=Abigail|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/09/05/former-komen-official-karen-handel-calls-planned-parenthood-a-schoolyard-thug.html|title=Ex-Komen Official Karen Handel Attacks Planned Parenthood 'Thugs' in New Book|publisher=The Daily Beast|date=September 5, 2012|accessdate=January 26, 2013}}</ref> She refers to Planned Parenthood as \"a blatantly partisan\" group of \"bullies\" that began a war with Komen over $700,000, an amount of money \"inconsequential\" to its $1 billion budget.<ref name=\"thedailybeast.com\"/>\n\n==2014 Senate election==\n{{See also|United States Senate election in Georgia, 2014}}\nOn May 17, 2013, Handel announced that she would be a candidate for the United States Senate.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/onpolitics/2013/05/17/karen-handel-senate-georgia-republican/2193343|work=USA Today|first1=Catalina|last1=Camia|title=Ex-Komen exec Karen Handel declares Ga. Senate bid|date=May 17, 2013}}</ref> Incumbent Senator [[Saxby Chambliss]] did not seek reelection. Handel was endorsed by former [[List of Governors of Alaska|Governor of Alaska]] [[Sarah Palin]] in March 2014.<ref>Joseph, Cameron. [http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/202086-is-palins-bark-bigger-than-her-bite Palin's bark bigger than her bite?], ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'', March 29, 2014.</ref> \n\nOne of her 2014 opponents, David Perdue, criticized her for never having attended college. Julianne Thompson, co-chair of the Atlanta Tea Party, replied to the charge by saying, \u201cOne of the most important things we look for in a leader is that person's ability to identify with the citizens they intend to govern.\u201d<ref>Warren, Michael; David Perdue on Karen Handel: 'High School Graduate'; Weekly Standard; April 3, 2014; [https://www.weeklystandard.com/michael-warren/david-perdue-on-karen-handel-high-school-graduate]</ref> \n\nIn May 2014, Handel came in third in the Republican Senate primary with 21.96% of the vote.<ref name=\"HandelKarenCongressBio2017\"/><ref name=\"results.enr.clarityelections.com\">{{cite web|url=http://results.enr.clarityelections.com/GA/51345/131442/en/summary.html|title=GA - Election Results|publisher=|accessdate=April 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n\n====2017====\n{{Main|Georgia's 6th congressional district special election, 2017}}\n[[File:Karen-Handel-PDK-Airshow-2017-06-10.jpg|thumb|300px|Karen Handel campaigning for 2017 run-off election]]\nIn February 2017, Handel announced a run for [[U.S. House of Representatives]] in the [[Georgia's 6th congressional district special election, 2017|2017 special election]] to fill a vacancy in [[Georgia's 6th congressional district]] against Democratic candidate [[Jon Ossoff]].<ref>Greg Bluestein, [http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2017/03/25/poll-jon-ossoff-karen-handel-rising-in-georgia-special-election/ Poll: Jon Ossoff, Karen Handel leading in Georgia special election], ''Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' (March 27, 2017).</ref> Former U.S. Senator [[Saxby Chambliss]] endorsed Handel.<ref>Path\u00e9, Simone. [http://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/jon-ossoff-karen-handel-georgia-special-election Jon Ossoff, Karen Handel Advance to Runoff in Georgia Special Election], ''[[Roll Call]]'', April 19, 2017.</ref>\n\nDuring the April 18, 2017, primary, Handel was the top Republican vote-getter in the 6th District race.<ref name=\"DeneryAJC04182017\"/> No candidate reached a majority of the vote, leading to a runoff election on June 20, 2017. Handel finished second in the [[jungle primary]] and faced Ossoff in the runoff. Ossoff received 48.1% of the vote and Handel received 19.8% of the vote.<ref name=\"GASOS04192017\">{{cite news|date=April 19, 2017|title=Unofficial Results|url=http://results.enr.clarityelections.com/GA/67317/Web02-state/#/|work=Georgia Secretary of State |location=[[Atlanta, Georgia]]|accessdate=April 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/04/18/politics/georgia-house-6th-special-election-jon-ossoff|title=Georgia special election goes to runoff as GOP gets wakeup call|accessdate=April 18, 2017|publisher=CNN}}</ref> Ossoff benefited by being one of only five Democrats on the ballot paper, with only one of those having previously participated in Georgia politics (former State Senator [[Ron Slotin]]), whereas Handel was one of eleven Republicans, four of whom had run for elected office on previous occasions, among them two former State Senators and one City Councilman.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}} [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Donald Trump]] congratulated her on advancing to the runoff and she welcomed his support.<ref name=\"USNews04192017\">{{cite news|last=Levy|first=Gabrielle|date=April 19, 2017|title=Handel wants Trump's help in Georgia runoff|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/national-news/articles/2017-04-19/karen-handel-wants-trumps-help-in-georgia-runoff-vs-ossoff|work=[[U.S. News and World Report]]|location=[[Washington, D.C.]]|accessdate=April 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAccording to an article by Elise Viebeck originally published by ''[[The Washington Post]]'', during the primary, Handel \"went out of her way not to mention Trump\".<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-georgia-republican-candidate-embracing-trump-20170430-story.html|title=GOP candidate now embracing Trump in Georgia's 6th District runoff|last=Weigel|first=Elise Viebeck, David|work=chicagotribune.com|access-date=May 10, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.myajc.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/6th-district-debate-ossoff-and-handel-clash-over-komen-and-comey/4yqKj7aJQZJxvyGPZwpkWK/|title=In 6th District debate, Ossoff and Handel clash over Komen and Comey|work=myajc|access-date=June 8, 2017|language=en}}</ref> According to the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', during the runoff against Ossoff, she \"embraced Trump\" and invoked his name.<ref name=\":6\"/><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2017/05/10/georgia-6th-handel-says-comeys-firing-was-probably-overdue|title=Georgia Sixth: Handel says Comey's firing was 'probably overdue'|accessdate=May 10, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":14\" /> She said that she would welcome Trump if he wanted to campaign with her.<ref name=\":6\"/> Handel and Trump held a fundraiser in April 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2017/04/28/at-fundraiser-trump-quips-to-handel-youd-better-win-6th-district-race/|title=Trump quips to Handel: \u2018You\u2019d better win\u2019 6th District race {{!}} Political Insider blog|access-date=May 30, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/29/us/politics/republicans-georgia.html|title=\u2018Narrowcast\u2019 Trump? Republicans Seek Formula to Keep House Majority|last=Peters|first=Jeremy W.|date=May 29, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 30, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nSpeaker of the House [[Paul Ryan]] campaigned for Handel, saying \"we need someone who is tested and true\",<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bluestein|first1=Greg|title=Ryan on Handel: \u2018We need someone who is tested and true\u2019|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2017/05/15/ryan-on-handel-we-need-someone-who-is-tested-and-true/|accessdate=June 14, 2017|publisher=AJC.com|date=May 16, 2017}}</ref> and Handel was endorsed by the [[United States Chamber of Commerce]], [[Susan B. Anthony List]], [[National Right to Life Committee]] and the [[National Rifle Association]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Karen Handel's Ratings and Endorsements |url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/69553/karen-handel#.WUCfltUrLrd|website=Vote Smart|publisher=votesmart.org|accessdate=June 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn June 15, 2017, Handel's home was the target of a \"suspicious package\" containing a \"white powdery substance\" and a threatening letter. Several of Handel's neighbors received similar suspicious packages in the mail. Handel stated, \"it is frustrating that my neighbors have been affected in this way. Steve and I know that running for public office often brings these kinds of challenges, but our neighbors did not sign up for this.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schultz|first1=Jaclyn|title=Karen Handel's home target of suspicious package|url=http://www.fox5atlanta.com/news/261681521-story|accessdate=June 16, 2017|publisher=Fox 5 Atlanta|date=June 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Elizaldi|first1=Elizabeth|title=Powder-filled envelopes sent to Georgia GOP candidate Karen Handel, neighbors|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/powder-filled-envelopes-found-ga-gop-candidate-neighborhood-article-1.3250811|accessdate=June 16, 2017|publisher=New York Daily News|date=June 15, 2017}}</ref> The [[FBI]] was called in to investigate.<ref>{{cite news|title=FBI joins investigation at Karen Handel's house|url=http://www.wsbtv.com/news/local/north-fulton-county/breaking-suspicious-package-shuts-down-street-where-karen-handel-lives/533890723|accessdate=June 16, 2017|publisher=WSB-TV 2 Atlanta|date=June 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe race received significant national attention after being highly touted as an early test of how the first few months of Donald Trump's presidency may have shifted the opinions or voter enthusiasm of suburban voters who live in swing districts.<ref>{{cite news|last=Barrow|first=Bill|title=Georgia special election shapes up as referendum on Trump|url=https://apnews.com/75e4d661a17743768202f23cd05d7a9e/house-race-trial-run-dems-gop-ahead-midtermshttps://apnews.com/75e4d661a17743768202f23cd05d7a9e/house-race-trial-run-dems-gop-ahead-midterms|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=February 14, 2017|accessdate=June 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Cillizza|first=Chris|date=May 9, 2017|title=The Georgia special election is now the most expensive House race ever|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/05/09/politics/georgia-6-special-election/index.html|publisher=[[CNN]]|accessdate=June 2, 2017}}</ref> Combined spending by both candidates' campaigns reached over $55 million, which was the most expensive U.S. House election in history.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/06/20/us/politics/georgia-6th-most-expensive-house-election.html|title=Who Financed the Georgia Sixth, the Most Expensive House Election Ever|last=Parlapiano|first=Alicia|date=June 20, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 23, 2017|last2=Shorey|first2=Rachel|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nOn June 20, 2017, Handel won the special election runoff and defeated Ossoff 51.87% to 48.13%.<ref name=\"HandelKarenCongressBio2017\"/> Following reports of the election results, ''[[The New York Times]]'' characterized the race as \"demoralizing for Democrats\".<ref>Bruni, Frank. [https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/20/opinion/georgia-election-karen-handel-jon-ossoff.html After Georgia Election, Democrats Are Demoralized, Again], ''[[New York Times]]'', June 20, 2017.</ref>\n\n====2018====\nIn the May 22 Democratic primary, Lucy McBath defeated Kevin Abel, Steven Knight Griffin, and Bobby Kaple. In the general election, Handel will also face Independent candidate Carlton Heston.\n\n===Tenure===\nHandel was sworn into office on June 26, 2017.<ref>{{cite web | title=Karen Handel Sworn In | url=http://www.fox5atlanta.com/news/263812828-story | date=June 26, 2017 | publisher=[[WAGA-TV]] | accessdate=June 27, 2017}}</ref> She became Georgia's first-ever Republican congresswoman.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Hallerman | first1=Tamar | title=Watch Karen Handel Get Sworn in as Georgia\u2019s First GOP Congresswoman | url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2017/06/26/watch-karen-handel-get-sworn-in-as-georgias-first-gop-congresswoman/ | date=June 26, 2017 | publisher=''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'' | accessdate=June 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn June 22, 2018, Handel, while presiding over the [[House of Representatives]], cited House Rule XVII to compel California Representative [[Ted Lieu]] to cease playing audio previously published by [[ProPublica]] that allegedly recorded the voices of children separated from their parents under the [[Trump administration family separation policy]].<ref>Collins, Eliza. [https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2018/06/22/ted-lieu-karen-handel-house-floor-dispute-crying-children-audio/725937002/ Reps. Ted Lieu and Karen Handel argue over audio of immigrant children played on House floor], [[USA Today]], June 22, 2018. </ref> The rule cited reads, \"A person on the floor of the House may not smoke or use a mobile electronic device that impairs decorum.\"<ref> [http://clerk.house.gov/legislative/house-rules.pdf> </ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|Committee on Education and the Workforce]]'''\n** Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary, and Secondary Education\n** Subcommittee on Workforce Protections\n*'''[[United States House Committee on the Judiciary|Committee on the Judiciary]]'''\n** Subcommittee on Regulatory Reform, Commercial and Antitrust Law\n** Subcommittee on the Constitution and Civil Justice\n* '''[[Republican Study Committee]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=Republican Study Committee|date=|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\nIn 2014, Handel described herself as an \"unwavering conservative fighter\" rather than a \"go along to get along\" Republican.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2014/05/gop-georgia-106748_Page3.html|title=GOP war revived in Georgia|last=Raju|first=Manu|work=POLITICO|access-date=May 13, 2017|language=en}}</ref> In the campaign for the [[United States Senate election in Georgia, 2014|2014 Senate seat]], she said that she would be a Senator in the mold of [[Ted Cruz]], and called on [[Mitch McConnell]] to resign from the Republican leadership of the Senate.<ref name=\":9\" /> In 2014, ''[[Politico]]'' described her as \"a [[Sarah Palin|Palin]]-style conservative\".<ref name=\":9\"/>\n\n=== Donald Trump ===\n\nHandel voiced support for President [[Donald Trump]]'s [[Dismissal of James Comey|May 9, 2017 firing]] of FBI Director [[James Comey]], stating, \"it's been clear for some time that FBI Director Comey has lost the confidence of Republicans, Democrats and broader institutions, and his removal as FBI Director was probably overdue\".<ref name=\":7\" /> Regarding reports Trump had disclosed classified information to Russia, Handel said that such reports represented \"potentially a gross assumption\" by the press, stating \"we have investigations underway...I would suggest that all of us would let the process play out, and let the facts take us where the facts take us.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2017/05/22/handel-on-trump-let-the-facts-take-us-where-the-facts-take-us/|title=Handel on Trump: \u2018Let the facts take us where the facts take us\u2019 {{!}} Political Insider blog|access-date=May 30, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":11\" /> In June 2017, she said that she was troubled by some of Trump's proposed cuts to federal research funds.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/moments-mattered-georgia-special-election-debate/story?id=47878880|title=5 moments that mattered in the Ga. special election debate|last=News|first=A. B. C.|date=June 6, 2017|website=ABC News|access-date=June 7, 2017}}</ref> She has also criticized Trump's use of [[Twitter]].<ref name=\":12\" /> In May 2018, Handel voiced her support for the [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u2013present)|Special Counsel investigation]], but adding \"Do it expeditiously. Do it fairly and justly and move it along.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://politics.myajc.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/rep-handel-mueller-investigation-should-continue-expeditiously/QIOJszLNa4NSMdCljQRJzM/|title=Rep. Handel: Mueller investigation should continue \u201cexpeditiously\u201d|work=politics.myajc|access-date=2018-07-10|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Domestic issues ===\n\n==== Environment ====\n\nHandel has said that the federal government's role in [[Climate change mitigation|combating climate change]] should be \"limited so that state and local government lead the way.\"<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2017/04/10/a-gop-split-over-climate-change-opens-in-georgia-special-election/|title=A GOP split over climate change opens in Georgia special election {{!}} Political Insider blog|last=Bluestein|first=Greg|access-date=May 12, 2017}}</ref> She supported President Trump's decision to withdraw the United States from the [[Paris Agreement|Paris Climate Agreement]].<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/08/us/politics/georgia-special-election-ossoff-handel.html|title=Takeaways From the Georgia Special Election Debate: A Sharper Clash|last=Burns|first=Alexander|date=June 8, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 8, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Asked if she accepted the [[Scientific opinion on climate change|scientific consensus on climate change]], Handel said, \"Clearly, there have been changes in the climate\" but did not say whether human activities contribute to climate change.<ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\":15\" />\n\n==== Health care ====\n\nHandel favors repealing the [[Affordable Care Act]] (Obamacare).<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.wabe.org/post/states-gop-senate-hopefuls-square-debate|title=State's GOP Senate Hopefuls Square Off In Debate|last=Eloy|first=Michell|accessdate=March 27, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://karenhandel.com/issues|title=Issues - Karen Handel for Congress|work=Karen Handel for Congress|accessdate=March 27, 2017}}</ref> She has expressed support for [[Tom Price (American politician)|Tom Price]]'s legislation to [[Efforts to repeal the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|replace]] Obamacare.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.salon.com/2014/05/21/georgia_gops_obamacare_fiasco_hypocrisy_evasion_and_insensitivity|title=Georgia GOP's Obamacare fiasco: Hypocrisy, evasion and insensitivity|last=Maloy|first=Simon|website=Salon|accessdate=March 27, 2017}}</ref> She supported the May 2017 version of the [[American Health Care Act]], the Republican Party's replacement plan for the Affordable Care Act.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2017/05/04/a-6th-district-rift-over-the-house-healthcare-plan-in-tom-prices-old-turf/|title=A 6th District rift over the House healthcare plan in Tom Price\u2019s old turf |access-date=May 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/republicans-obamacare-repeal-wont-sink-us-in-2018/article/2622485|title=Republicans: Obamacare repeal won't sink us in 2018|last=Drucker|first=David M.|work=Washington Examiner|access-date=May 10, 2017|language=en}}</ref> In a June 2017 debate, she stated that she would never support a bill that reduced protections for preexisting conditions and said that the AHCA did no such thing, while ''[[CNN]]'' noted that independent [[Fact checking|fact-checkers]] have found that the May 2017 version of AHCA would reduce protections for preexisting conditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/06/politics/jon-ossoff-karen-handel-georgia-debate/index.html|title=Handel, Ossoff dance around Trump in Georgia House race debate|last=CNN|first=Eric Bradner|website=CNN|access-date=June 7, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/in-georgia-ossoff-handel-cast-each-other-as-rubber-stamps/2017/06/06/ea97bd02-4b2a-11e7-987c-42ab5745db2e_story.html|title=In Georgia, Ossoff, Handel cast each other as rubber stamps|website=Washington Post|access-date=June 7, 2017}}</ref> Handel said, \"I reject the premise of CBO\", referring to the [[Congressional Budget Office]] estimate that 23 million more Americans would be uninsured if the May 2017 version of AHCA were to become law.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref>{{Cite news |title=The Daily 202: Ohio is hurting because of Obamacare\u2019s uncertain future, but Trumpcare could make matters worse |last=Hohmann |first=James |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/paloma/daily-202/2017/06/07/daily-202-ohio-is-hurting-because-of-obamacare-s-uncertain-future-but-trumpcare-could-make-matters-worse/5937d0b2e9b69b2fb981dc7c/|work=Washington Post|access-date=June 7, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n====Voter identification requirements ====\n\nHandel supports laws that require Americans to show photo identification before voting.<ref name=\"Morrow41817\" />\n\n=== Economic issues ===\n\n==== Jobs ====\n\nIn a June 2017 debate, Handel stated that she opposed a minimum wage, saying \"This is an example of a fundamental difference between a liberal and a conservative. I do not support a livable wage.\"<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":13\" /> Handel stated \"The private sector creates good paying jobs when we have a robust economy with lower taxes and less regulation.\"<ref name=\":13\" />\n\n==== Tax reform ====\n\nHandel has described the tax system as comprising \"Onerous, punitive regulations, costly red tape, and a complex tax structure with rates that are too high are limiting business expansion and job growth.\"<ref name=\"Morrow41817\" />\n\nHandel voted in favor of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"Almukhtar\">{{cite web|last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah|title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html?_r=0|website=The New York Times|accessdate=25 December 2017|date=19 December 2017}}</ref> She called the passing of the bill a \"historic moment\" and said that the bill would be \"transformative for hardworking American families and American companies, especially our small businesses.\" She said that \"hardworking Americans\" will \"keep more of their money.\" She also said that the bill would enable small businesses to \"innovate and grow.\"<ref name=\"Parker122017\">{{cite web|last1=Parker|first1=Wendy|title=Handel, Isakson and Perdue hail passage of tax reform bill|url=https://www.eastcobbnews.com/tag/tax-reform-bill/|website=East Cobb News|accessdate=25 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== International issues ===\n\n==== Immigration ====\nHandel opposed the [[Border Security, Economic Opportunity, and Immigration Modernization Act of 2013|bipartisan Senate \"Gang of Eight\" bill]], which would have provided a [[Immigration reform|pathway to citizenship]] for the estimated 11 million [[Illegal immigration to the United States|undocumented immigrants]] in the United States.<ref name=\":2\"/> She opposes an automatic path to citizenship, saying, \"These immigrants have come to our country and blatantly disregarded our laws. We cannot, we should not reward that. No amnesty. No ability to vote.\"<ref name=\":8\"/>\n\nShe supports building a [[Mexico\u2013United States barrier|wall]] along the US-Mexico border. \"True national security means securing our borders, she said, \"the current immigration system is broken, and we MUST fix it.\"<ref name=\"Morrow41817\" />\n\n=== Social issues ===\n\n==== Abortion ====\n\nHandel opposes [[abortion]]<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/08/us/after-outcry-a-top-official-resigns-at-komen-cancer-charity.html|title=After Outcry, Karen Handel Resigns From Komen|last=Preston|first=Jennifer|date=February 7, 2012|work=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|accessdate=March 27, 2017}}</ref> and favors eliminating government funding for Planned Parenthood.<ref name=\":4\" /> She wrote a book, ''Planned Bullyhood: The Truth Behind the Headlines about the Planned Parenthood Funding Battle with Susan G. Komen for the Cure'' about the subject.<ref name=\"Morrow41817\">{{cite web|last1=Morrow|first1=Brendan|title=Karen Handel\u2019s Political Positions: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know|url=http://heavy.com/news/2017/04/karen-handel-political-positions-views-on-issues/|website=Heavy|accessdate=25 December 2017|date=18 April 2017}}</ref>\nShe opposes [[embryonic stem cell]] research.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/Social/Karen_Handel_Abortion.htm|title=Karen Handel on Abortion|website=www.ontheissues.org|access-date=March 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/karen-handel-resigns-5-times-ex-komen-vps-views-ignited-controversy-406992|title=Karen Handel Resigns: 5 Times Ex-Komen VP's Views Ignited Controversy|date=February 7, 2012|work=International Business Times|accessdate=March 30, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/karen-handel-resigns-5-times-ex-komen-vps-views-ignited-controversy-406992|title=Karen Handel Resigns: 5 Times Ex-Komen VP's Views Ignited Controversy|date=February 7, 2012|work=International Business Times|access-date=May 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== LGBT rights ====\n\nHandel opposes [[Same-sex marriage in the United States|same-sex marriage]] and [[Same-sex unions in the United States|same-sex civil unions]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/senate-races/206172-gingrey-handel-promoted-teenage-homosexuality|title=Gingrey: Handel 'promoted teenage homosexuality'|last=Taylor|first=Jessica|date=May 14, 2014|work=TheHill|access-date=May 21, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/2017/4/19/republican-georgia-race-has-anti-lgbt-antichoice-history|title=Republican in Georgia Race Has Anti-LGBT, Antichoice History|date=April 19, 2017|access-date=May 21, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> She has voted against legislation that would give [[Domestic partnership in the United States|domestic partner benefits]].<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/local-govt--politics/handel-challenging-past-led-deliberate-future/aSnt38XK1O7ZGW1YC0aMcP/|title=Handel's challenging past led to deliberate future|last=Sheinin|first=Aaron Gould|website=ajc|access-date=May 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://chronicle.augusta.com/metro-georgia-governor/2010-06-11/handel-grilled-over-support-gay-rights|title=Handel is grilled over support for gay rights|access-date=May 21, 2017|language=en}}</ref> She opposes the [[LGBT adoption|adoption&nbsp;of children by gay individuals]], stating that it \"is not the best household for a child.\"<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://qa.politifact.com/georgia/statements/2010/jun/07/nathan-deal/deal-claims-handel-supported-gay-adoption/|title=Deal claims Handel supported gay adoption|work=@politifact|access-date=May 21, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thegavoice.com/karen-handel-i-would-consider-banning-gay-adoption/|title=Karen Handel: \u2018I would consider\u2019 banning gay adoption|date=2010-07-14|work=Georgia Voice - Gay & LGBT Atlanta News|access-date=2018-01-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHandel is [[Roman Catholic]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lifesitenews.com/news/pro-life-planned-bullyhood-author-advances-to-georgia-run-off-election|title=Pro-life \u2018Planned Bullyhood\u2019 author advances to Georgia run-off election|work=LifeSiteNews|access-date=June 21, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> She is married to Steve Handel.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commonscat}}\n* [https://handel.house.gov/ Congresswoman Karen Handel]\n* [http://www.karenhandel.com/ Campaign website] \n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Georgia/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Karen_Handel_%5BR-6%5D}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=H001078 }}\n*{{C-SPAN|Karen Handel}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Cathy Cox]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State of Georgia]]|years=2007\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Brian Kemp]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| state=Georgia\n| district=6\n| before=[[Tom Price (American politician)|Tom Price]]\n| start=June 20, 2